Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Boil a full #kettle{}.

Pop the @diced butternut squash{300%g} onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with
@oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a
single layer.

> Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden and tender,
~{18-20%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

In the meantime, pour the boiled water from your kettle into a large #saucepan{}
with @salt{1/4%tsp} on high heat.

Add the @basmati rice{150%g} and cook for ~{10-12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and pop back in the pan. Cover with a #lid{}
and leave to the side until ready to serve.

While the rice cooks, peel and grate the @garlic clove{2}.

Zest and halve the @lime{1}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine the @soured cream{75%g} and lime zest.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot,
stir in the garlic, @tomato puree{30%g} and @Cajun spice mix{1%sachet}. Cook until
fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> Add less Cajun spice if you'd prefer things milder.

Lower to medium heat, then add the @water{100%ml} and @vegetable stock paste{15%g}.
Simmer until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add the @peas{120%g}, cooked rice, @honey{15%g} and @butter{20%g} to the frying pan.
Stir to combine.

> If your honey has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for 1 min.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once roasted, stir the sweet potato through the spicy rice. Squeeze in the juice
from half the lime. Taste and season with salt and pepper if needed. Add a splash
of @?water{} if it's a little too dry.

When ready, share the spicy rice between your bowls.

Crumble over the @Greek style salad cheese{50%g} and top with a dollop of zesty
soured cream.

Serve with any remaining lime cut into wedges for squeezing over.

Enjoy!

